From b65af4087efc0c94cc3ec7a4b92cb1e1dc906673 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Chronium Build <chronium@interlink.local>
Date: Mon, 8 Jun 2026 09:38:47 +0700
Subject: [PATCH 10/14] chronium: hide navigator.webdriver + per-profile IANA
 timezone override
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Two unrelated but small surfaces in one patch. Both gated by the
existing FingerprintState plumbing.

navigator.webdriver
  Plan §5 #18 'CDP hide webdriver'. When a fingerprint profile is
  active, Navigator::webdriver() returns false unconditionally,
  shortcircuiting the AutomationControlled runtime feature and the
  DevTools probe override. Real Chrome user sessions return false;
  fingerprinters treat any true value as a hard automation flag
  regardless of how well the rest of the fingerprint matches.

IANA timezone override (plan §5 #12)
  TimeZoneController::Init() now reads --fingerprint-timezone
  directly from the command line and calls the same
  SetTimeZoneOverride() RAII path DevTools emulation uses. The
  returned handle is intentionally leaked so the override persists
  for the renderer process lifetime.

  KEY DESIGN POINT: Init() runs from CoreInitializer (invoked by
  InitializeWebKit in RenderThreadImpl) BEFORE
  ChromeContentRendererClient::RenderThreadStarted populates
  FingerprintState. So we must read the command-line switch
  directly here — the switch is set at process spawn so it's
  always available. We also mirror it into FingerprintState so
  later patches that consume the typed accessor see a consistent
  view.

  This drives ICU's default time zone and triggers
  v8::Isolate::DateTimeConfigurationChangeNotification under the
  hood, so JS Date / Intl.DateTimeFormat / getTimezoneOffset all
  return values consistent with the profile's IANA id.

Verified on profile B with timezone = 'Asia/Tokyo':
  navigator.webdriver                              -> false
  new Date().getTimezoneOffset()                   -> -540
  Intl.DateTimeFormat().resolvedOptions().timeZone -> 'Asia/Tokyo'
  new Date().toString()                            -> '... GMT+0900
                                                       (Japan
                                                       Standard
                                                       Time)'

